Please do the following:

Analysis

1. Load and Normalize Data

Column names are already in snake_case. We convert categorical variables to explicit factors with meaningful level ordering and recode the income variable to an ordered factor.

# Define ordered income levels
income_levels <- c(
  "$0â$24,999",
  "$25,000â$49,999",
  "$50,000â$74,999",
  "$75,000â$99,999",
  "$100,000â$124,999",
  "$125,000â$149,999",
  "$150,000â$174,999",
  "$175,000+"
)

# Define ordered education levels
edu_levels <- c("less_than_hs", "hs", "some_college", "college", "post_grad")
edu_labels <- c("Less than HS", "High School", "Some College", "College", "Post-Grad")

df <- df |>
  mutate(
    # Binary outcome as factor
    received_comprehensive_postnatal_care = factor(
      received_comprehensive_postnatal_care,
      levels = c(0, 1),
      labels = c("No", "Yes")
    ),

    # Ordered factors
    self_report_income = factor(self_report_income, levels = income_levels, ordered = TRUE),
    edu = factor(edu, levels = edu_levels, labels = edu_labels, ordered = TRUE),

    # Unordered categorical
    race_ethnicity = factor(race_ethnicity),
    insurance = factor(insurance, levels = c("no_insurance", "state_provided", "private")),
    job_type = factor(job_type),
    state = factor(state),
    provider_id = factor(provider_id),

    # Binary indicators remain numeric (0/1) for modeling
    across(
      c(obesity, multiple_gestation, diabetes, heart_disease,
        placenta_previa, hypertension, gest_hypertension, preeclampsia),
      as.integer
    )
  )

4. Count Model: Comorbidity Count

Construct the Outcome

df <- df |>
  mutate(
    comorbidity_count = obesity + multiple_gestation + diabetes +
      heart_disease + placenta_previa + hypertension +
      gest_hypertension + preeclampsia
  )

cat("Comorbidity count distribution:\n")
Comorbidity count distribution:
table(df$comorbidity_count) |> print()

    0     1     2     3     4     5     6     7 
21350 16560  8359  2873   706   134    17     1 
cat("\nMean:", round(mean(df$comorbidity_count), 3),
    " Variance:", round(var(df$comorbidity_count), 3), "\n")

Mean: 0.91  Variance: 0.995

Model Selection: Poisson vs.Â Negative Binomial

For count data, Poisson regression assumes the mean equals the variance (equidispersion). If the variance exceeds the mean, overdispersion is present and a negative binomial model is more appropriate because it adds a dispersion parameter.

mean_cc <- mean(df$comorbidity_count)
var_cc <- var(df$comorbidity_count)
cat("Mean:", round(mean_cc, 3), "\n")
Mean: 0.91 
cat("Variance:", round(var_cc, 3), "\n")
Variance: 0.995 
cat("Variance / Mean ratio:", round(var_cc / mean_cc, 3), "\n")
Variance / Mean ratio: 1.094 
fit_pois <- glm(
  comorbidity_count ~ age + self_report_income + edu + race_ethnicity +
    insurance + job_type + dependents + distance_to_provider +
    received_comprehensive_postnatal_care,
  data = df,
  family = poisson(link = "log")
)
# Residual deviance / df as quick overdispersion check
deviance_ratio <- deviance(fit_pois) / df.residual(fit_pois)
cat("Residual deviance / df:", round(deviance_ratio, 3), "\n")
Residual deviance / df: 1.212 
cat("If substantially > 1, overdispersion is present.\n")
If substantially > 1, overdispersion is present.
fit_nb <- glm.nb(
  comorbidity_count ~ age + self_report_income + edu + race_ethnicity +
    insurance + job_type + dependents + distance_to_provider +
    received_comprehensive_postnatal_care,
  data = df
)

cat("Negative binomial theta:", round(fit_nb$theta, 3), "\n")
Negative binomial theta: 10.232 
cat("(Smaller theta = more overdispersion; as theta -> Inf, NB -> Poisson)\n")
(Smaller theta = more overdispersion; as theta -> Inf, NB -> Poisson)

Model Comparison

aic_comp <- tibble(
  Model = c("Poisson", "Negative Binomial"),
  AIC = c(AIC(fit_pois), AIC(fit_nb)),
  `Log-Likelihood` = c(logLik(fit_pois), logLik(fit_nb))
)

aic_comp |>
  kable(digits = 1) |>
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = "striped", full_width = FALSE)
Model AIC Log-Likelihood
Poisson 127022.3 -63484.1
Negative Binomial 126854.0 -63399.0 
# Likelihood ratio test: NB vs Poisson (NB nests Poisson when theta -> Inf)
lr_stat <- 2 * (logLik(fit_nb) - logLik(fit_pois))
lr_pval <- pchisq(as.numeric(lr_stat), df = 1, lower.tail = FALSE)
cat("LR test statistic:", round(as.numeric(lr_stat), 1), "\n")
LR test statistic: 170.3 
cat("p-value:", format.pval(lr_pval), "\n")
p-value: < 2.22e-16

Decision: We select the negative binomial model based on (1) the variance-to-mean ratio exceeding 1, (2) lower AIC, and (3) a significant likelihood ratio test rejecting the Poisson constraint.

Interpretable Results: Incidence Rate Ratios

irr_table <- tidy(fit_nb, conf.int = TRUE, exponentiate = TRUE) |>
  filter(term != "(Intercept)") |>
  mutate(
    significance = case_when(
      p.value < 0.001 ~ "***",
      p.value < 0.01  ~ "**",
      p.value < 0.05  ~ "*",
      TRUE            ~ ""
    )
  ) |>
  select(term, IRR = estimate, `2.5%` = conf.low, `97.5%` = conf.high,
         p.value, significance)

5. Diagnostics and Responsible Reporting

Model Diagnostics

diag_df <- tibble(
  fitted = fitted(fit_nb),
  pearson_resid = residuals(fit_nb, type = "pearson"),
  deviance_resid = residuals(fit_nb, type = "deviance")
)

p_resid_fitted <- ggplot(diag_df, aes(x = fitted, y = pearson_resid)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.05, size = 0.5) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, color = "red", linetype = "dashed") +
  geom_smooth(method = "loess", se = FALSE, color = "blue", linewidth = 0.8) +
  labs(x = "Fitted Values", y = "Pearson Residuals",
       title = "Residuals vs Fitted") +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 12)

p_resid_hist <- ggplot(diag_df, aes(x = deviance_resid)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 60, fill = "steelblue", alpha = 0.7) +
  labs(x = "Deviance Residuals", y = "Count",
       title = "Deviance Residual Distribution") +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 12)

p_resid_fitted + p_resid_hist
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
# Compare observed vs predicted count frequencies
obs_freq <- table(df$comorbidity_count)
pred_probs <- sapply(as.integer(names(obs_freq)), function(k) {
  mean(dnbinom(k, mu = fitted(fit_nb), size = fit_nb$theta))
})

rootogram_df <- tibble(
  count = as.integer(names(obs_freq)),
  observed = as.numeric(obs_freq) / nrow(df),
  expected = pred_probs
)

rootogram_df |>
  pivot_longer(cols = c(observed, expected), names_to = "type", values_to = "proportion") |>
  ggplot(aes(x = count, y = proportion, fill = type)) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge", alpha = 0.8) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("observed" = "steelblue", "expected" = "coral"),
                    name = NULL) +
  labs(
    x = "Comorbidity Count",
    y = "Proportion",
    title = "Observed vs. Expected Frequencies (Negative Binomial)"
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 13)

Assumptions and Limitations

Model assumptions:

  1. Conditional independence: Observations are assumed independent given covariates. However, patients are nested within providers (provider_id) and states, introducing potential clustering. A mixed-effects model (e.g., glmer.nb()) could account for this, but was not pursued here for parsimony.

  2. Correct mean structure: We assume the log-linear specification captures the true relationship between covariates and the comorbidity count. No interactions or nonlinear terms for continuous predictors (e.g., age, distance) were included. Residual diagnostics above provide a visual check.

  3. Negative binomial distributional assumption: The NB model adds a dispersion parameter relative to Poisson. The observed-vs-expected count comparison above assesses goodness-of-fit.

Limitations:

  • Cross-sectional, observational data. All associations should be interpreted as correlations, not causal effects. Unmeasured confounders (e.g., access to prenatal care, health literacy, genetic factors) are likely present.

  • Self-reported income. Subject to reporting bias and may not reflect actual economic resources (wealth, debt, cost of living).

  • Synthetic data. This dataset is simulated. Results characterize the data-generating process, not real-world maternal health patterns.

  • No adjustment for multiple comparisons. With many predictors, some nominally significant results may be spurious.

  • Clustering ignored. Patients within the same provider or state may share unobserved characteristics. Standard errors may be underestimated.

Summary of Changes

  1. Loaded and normalized the 50,000-row dataset. Converted categorical columns (self_report_income, edu, race_ethnicity, insurance, job_type, state, provider_id) to factors with explicit levels. Ordered factors were used for income and education. The binary outcome received_comprehensive_postnatal_care was converted to a labeled factor.

  2. Summarized the data: 50,000 rows, 20 columns, zero missing values. Reported descriptive statistics for all numeric and categorical variables. Flagged the right-skewed distance distribution and confirmed all binary indicators were within expected ranges.

  3. Created visualizations showing postnatal care receipt by insurance status and race/ethnicity, distance-to-provider distributions by care status, and boxplots of distance by insurance and race.

  4. Built comorbidity_count as the sum of 8 binary indicators. Compared Poisson and negative binomial models using AIC and a likelihood ratio test. The negative binomial was selected due to overdispersion. Reported incidence rate ratios with 95% confidence intervals and a coefficient plot.

  5. Reported responsibly with residual diagnostics, an observed-vs-expected count comparison, and explicit discussion of assumptions (independence, log-linear mean, NB distribution) and limitations (observational design, self-report bias, synthetic data, clustering).
